Using OpenStreetMap data in R

Brendan Oâ€™Dowd

2023-01-03

Context

I once had to produce a map examining a land use transition from bogs for peat-cutting to areas for windfarms. I decided it would be useful to import outlines of bogs and locations of wind turbines from OpenStreetMaps.

Setup

We need a couple of packages to start out with. Tidyverse is used for general data manipulation. The sf package is for managing and plotting maps (shapes, more generally) in R. It is installed with tidyverse but not loaded with it. The osmdata package allows us to import OpenStreetMap data into R as either â€˜sfâ€™ or â€˜spâ€™ objects (prefer â€˜sfâ€™ objects). I also need a map of Irish counties. You can get such a map from several places; here I use my own map of 166 local electoral areas and convert that into a county map.

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(osmdata)
library(cowplot)
county_map <- st_read("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/brendanjodowd/maps/main/lea_166.geojson") %>% 
  group_by(COUNTY) %>% 
  summarise(geometry = st_union(geometry) , AREA=sum(AREA))

Importing data from OpenStreetMaps

We first create an â€˜Overpass queryâ€™ for OpenStreetMaps using the function opq. This can take as its argument the name of a place, or a bounding box using latitude and longitude coordinates. See the help section on that function for further details. Then the function add_osm_feature specifies the kinds of map objects that you want to return. It requires both a key and a value argument. The key argument is a feature key, sort of like a category of map object. Options include â€˜boundaryâ€™, â€˜amenityâ€™, and â€˜naturalâ€™. The value argument is a specific class of object for that feature key. There is a very wide range of values available within the different keys, such as â€˜forestâ€™, â€˜supermarketâ€™, â€˜cathedralâ€™. Have a look at this list of features for a sense of what can be imported. Iâ€™m not sure if that list is exhaustive, or whether everything on it can be easily imported.

Here I am using key = "natural and value = "wetland". Note that there isnâ€™t a map object for â€˜bogsâ€™ we might understand them in Ireland, but the wetlands matched my requirements for this project.

At the point of the add_osm_feature function, all you have done is defined the query that you want to run, you havenâ€™t actually imported any data yet. That is done by the function osmdata_sf, which gathers the data and outputs an sf object. This function can take a while to run, and may not always run successfully, so it may be best to save the resulting object to file at this point before you make further modifications.

The bogs object is a list with a whole load of different variables inside, most of them empty. All I really need is the element osm_polygons.

An optional extra step here is to pass the bogs sf object through the function ms_simplify from the rmapshaper package. This simplifies polygons, reducing their size. There are parameters to that function to tailor the process, but I find that the default settings are usually fine.

bogs <- opq("Ireland") %>% 
  add_osm_feature(key = "natural" , value = "wetland") %>% 
  osmdata_sf()

bogs <- bogs$osm_polygons

bogs <- rmapshaper::ms_simplify(bogs)

Letâ€™s have a look at what weâ€™ve got.

ggplot(county_map) + geom_sf() + 
  geom_sf(data = bogs , fill="red" , colour = "red")

Wind turbines

Ok, letâ€™s get the wind turbines. I use key = "power" and value = "generator". Note that this imports lots of different devices that generate electricity, but I can filter to wind turbines later on.

turbines_query <- opq("Ireland") %>% 
  add_osm_feature(key = "power" , value = "generator") %>% 
  osmdata_sf()

Just as I only needed osm_polygons for the bogs (or wetlands), here all I require is the element osm_points. I select a couple of variables that I want from that dataframe, and filter so that I only have wind turbines in my selection. (There are 9 different generator types in Ireland at the time of writing, including over 3,000 wind turbines and over a hundred each of PV and combustion/thermal generators).

turbines <- turbines$osm_points %>% 
  select(name, generator.method , generator.output.electricity, 
         generator.source, manufacturer, operator) %>% 
  filter(generator.method=="wind_turbine")

Letâ€™s see what we have.

ggplot(county_map) + geom_sf() + 
  geom_sf(data = turbines , colour="red")

Thereâ€™s actually a new windfarm in a part of Tipperary that I wanted to include. I found these coordinates manually from Google Maps, and they can be turned into an sf object as shown below. Their coordinate reference system (CRS) is set to be the same as that for county_map (WGS 84).

new_sites <- tribble(
  ~lat , ~long,
  52.61594839110318, -7.69242746150073,
  52.61276941295214, -7.686762636061125,
  52.60836536508515, -7.682256524916086,
  52.636185727368925, -7.660562886949663,
  52.64386809365363, -7.651893987413578,
  52.64449732500331, -7.66927492954084,
  52.65019471092566, -7.659118918231185,
  52.65509578182991, -7.661757585929191,
  52.65509578182991, -7.64464259368543,
  52.65822504258744, -7.651925569108475,
  52.664671978288375, -7.655918392931982,
  52.665973321164486, -7.641241345202222,
  52.671348708560096, -7.649956877758161,
  52.67446892090545, -7.657981275577273
  ) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("long", "lat"), crs = st_crs(county_map))

Plotting

Ok, letâ€™s map all of this for a section of Tipperary. Iâ€™m cropping to this part of the country using xlim and ylim. Turbines are plotted as open circles using shape=1 (there are a couple of places online where you can check out all the different point shapes available, here is one website that has them). Axes and other unwanted plot items are removed using theme_void. The background is set to a dark grey colour using the plot.background argument within a theme function.

ggplot(county_map)+
  geom_sf(size=1.5, fill=NA , colour = "white") +
  geom_sf(data=bogs, fill="#58764C", colour="#58764C", size=1) +
  geom_sf(data=turbines, colour = "#00A2FF", shape=1, size=2 ) + 
  geom_sf(data=new_sites, colour = "red" , shape=1, size=2 ) + 
  xlim(-8.4,-7.3) + ylim(52.5, 53.1) + 
  theme_void() + 
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#2B2727"))
